  "slug": "gougeres-cheese-choux",
  "title": "Gougères",
  "subtitle": "Savoury cheese choux puffs",
  "excerpt": "The Burgundian aperitif puff: choux pastry beaten with grated Gruyère and Parmesan, piped in walnut-sized rounds, and baked until deep gold. Twenty-four gougères, served warm with wine.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Marie-Antoine Carême (1833) and Auguste Escoffier (1903): document the gougère as a Burgundian regional savoury choux. The household form (cheese beaten into the choux paste before piping) is documented across pre-1928 French sources.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Gougères are the savoury cousin of the cream puff: the same choux pastry method (boil, cook out flour, beat in eggs) but with grated Gruyère and Parmesan beaten through the paste at the end. Piped in walnut-sized rounds and baked, they puff up hollow and crisp, with the cheese giving a deep gold colour and a savoury edge.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "A Burgundian aperitif. Serve warm with a glass of chilled white wine. Cold gougères revive in a hot oven for two or three minutes.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
