      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Boil, cook out, beat in eggs",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the oven to 200°C fan and line two baking trays. Bring the {{water}}, {{whole-milk}}, {{unsalted-butter}} and {{sea-salt-fine}} to a rolling boil. Take off the heat and tip in the sifted {{plain-flour}}; beat hard to a smooth paste. Return to a low heat and beat for 2 minutes until the paste leaves the pan clean. Tip into a bowl. Beat in the {{eggs}} a quarter at a time until the paste flows in a slow ribbon and holds a brief V on the spoon.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Cheese in, pipe",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Beat in three-quarters of the {{gruyere}}, all the {{parmesan}}, the {{black-pepper-ground}} and the {{nutmeg-ground}}. Fill a piping bag with a 12 mm round tip. Pipe 24 walnut-sized rounds onto the trays with 4 cm between each. Scatter the reserved Gruyère over the tops.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bake, 25 minutes",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bake at 200°C fan for 18 minutes, then drop to 170°C for another 10 minutes; the puffs should be deep gold, the cheese should be melted, and they should feel firm and light when lifted. Serve warm.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
